+
+The selected trajectory is labeled by an HK or HKL reflection family, with $Q_r$ supplied as secondary numerical information when useful. Internal labels such as M1, M2, plus branch, or minus branch are used only if the caption defines how they map onto equivalent reflections in the hexagonal reciprocal lattice. A compact HK-family label may represent all symmetry-equivalent in-plane reflections with the same in-plane radius, but that convention has to be stated wherever it is used.
+
+With the geometry and mosaic/profile state fixed, the structure-factor stage varies the crystallographic parameters that enter Eq.~\eqref{eq:structure_factor}: lattice constants, site coordinates, occupancies, and anisotropic displacement terms. The fitted lattice, coordinate, occupancy, and displacement parameters remain within the structural-prior ranges summarized in Table S1 of the supporting information. This keeps the main-text emphasis on the line-shape overlays while recording that the ordered-film agreement does not require unphysical changes to the average Bi$_2$Te$_3$ or Bi$_2$Se$_3$ structures.\cite{Trueblood1996,Mansour2014,Steiner2014,Callaert2019}
+
+The local profile checks isolate line-shape information from integrated intensity information. The specular-cap and off-specular-arc profiles are reproduced by the same Gaussian-plus-Lorentzian mosaic profile, and the final $Q_z$ projection overlays demonstrate whether the ordered structure-factor description is sufficient within the experimental resolution. This ordered-film agreement is the baseline result of the paper and appears before any PbI$_2$ or stacking-disorder discussion is introduced.
